    <h1 id="what-is-cloud?">What is Cloud?</h1>
    <p>Cloud refers to servers that are accessed over the internet and the software and databases that run on those servers. Cloud servers are located in data centers all over the world. By using cloud computing, companies don’t have to manage physical servers or run software applications on their machines.</p>
    <h1 id="what-is-azure?">What is Azure?</h1>
    <p>Azure is Microsoft's cloud platform. It provides a wide variety of services, including computing power, storage, and networking, allowing users to build, deploy, and manage applications and services through a global network of data centers.</p>
    <h1 id="what-is-cloud-service?">What is Cloud Service?</h1>
    <p>Cloud services refer to a range of services delivered over the internet. They include software, platforms, and infrastructure, allowing businesses to utilize resources without owning physical hardware.</p>
    <h1 id="what-is-cloud-computing?">What is Cloud Computing?</h1>
    <p>Cloud computing is the delivery of different services through the internet, including data storage, servers, databases, networking, and software. Cloud computing provides businesses and individuals the ability to store files and applications on remote servers rather than on physical hardware.</p>
    <h1 id="what-is-iaas,-paas,-and-saas?">What is IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS?</h1>
    <h3 id="iaas-(infrastructure-as-a-service)">IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)</h3>
    <p>
        IaaS provides essential computing, storage, and networking resources on-demand, often on a pay-as-you-go basis. Examples include:
        - <strong>Azure Virtual Machines</strong>
        - <strong>Amazon EC2</strong>
    </p>
    <h3 id="paas-(platform-as-a-service)">PaaS (Platform as a Service)</h3>
    <p>
        PaaS provides a framework for developers that they can build upon and use to create customized applications. Examples include:
        - <strong>Azure App Services</strong>
        - <strong>Google App Engine</strong>
    </p>
    <h3 id="saas-(software-as-a-service)">SaaS (Software as a Service)</h3>
    <p>
        SaaS is a software distribution model in which third-party providers host applications and make them available to customers over the internet. Examples include:
        - <strong>Microsoft 365</strong>
        - <strong>Google Workspace</strong>
    </p>
    <h1 id="why-is-azure-storage-account-required?">Why is Azure Storage Account Required?</h1>
    <p>An Azure Storage account provides a unique namespace for your Azure Storage data, which includes blobs, files, queues, and tables. Without a storage account, you cannot store any data in Azure. It serves as a container to hold different storage services and types.</p>
    <h1 id="how-to-create-different-types-of-azure-storage-resources-in-the-azure-portal">How to Create Different Types of Azure Storage Resources in the Azure Portal</h1>
    <h3 id="step-by-step-guide-using-azure-portal">Step-by-step guide using Azure Portal</h3>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Log into Azure Portal</strong>: Visit <a href="https://portal.azure.com">portal.azure.com</a> and log in with your credentials.</li>
        <li><strong>Create a Resource</strong>: In the left-hand navigation, click on "Create a resource" and search for "Storage account."</li>
        <li>
            <strong>Configure Basics</strong>:
            <ul>
                <li>Subscription: Choose the correct subscription.</li>
                <li>Resource Group: Either select an existing resource group or create a new one.</li>
                <li>Storage Account Name: Choose a globally unique name.</li>
                <li>Region: Choose the closest region.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Configure Storage Options</strong>:
            <ul>
                <li>Performance: Select either Standard or Premium.</li>
                <li>Redundancy: Choose from options like LRS, GRS, etc.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Review and Create</strong>: After reviewing the settings, click "Create."</li>
    </ol>
